data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(value)` to resolve to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime (or may fail to compile in some contexts).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both force the compiler to bind to the `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which is representable in expression trees. The same issue applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead.
